AU  - Ginzburg, LR
AU  - Inchausti, P
TI  - Asymmetry of population cycles: abundance-growth representation of hidden causes of ecological dynamics
T2  - OIKOS
AB  - The analysis of time series of 20 species of forest insects and vertebrates showed that cyclic populations take longer, typically 50% more time, to grow than to decline. The asymmetry of cycles does not differ significantly among different taxa (insects, small and large mammals and birds) and is not associated with the periods of oscillation. The asymmetric nature of population cycles may be due to the existence of a maximum value of the per capita growth rate that constrains the growing phase of the cycle but does not impose a limit in the rate of decline. By including the constraint on the population growth rate, a second order model can produce stable limit cycles regardless of the actual ecological mechanism generating the cyclic dynamics.
