TI  - Identifying and locating tree decline and dieback in Donana Biological Reserve with Venus VM5 images
T2  - IGARSS 2025-2025 IEEE INTERNATIONAL GEOSCIENCE AND REMOTE SENSING SYMPOSIUM
CP  - 2025 International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium-IGARSS-Annual
AB  - Global forest decline is been observed across different ecosystems. Time series of Earth Observation images are very useful to detect and locate sudden drops of vegetation greenness. However, the increasing frequency of disturbances linked to global change (drought, pests, etc.) can lead to a scattered response by each individual tree. Hence, evidence of tree decay becomes harder to show due to constraint posed by sensors spatial resolution. In this work, we leverage images collected by the Venus VM5 satellite mission during more than 2 years over Donana National Park. In situ observations have reported during 2022 a significant dieback of old tall trees which has been more dramatic for remnant Cork Oaks. Most of these trees are found isolated or small patches with a maximum crown area below the spatial resolution of available optical time series of Earth Observation images. In this work we test the enhancement of spatial and temporal resolution provided by Venus VM5 to detect and locate trees or stands undergoing canopy decline leading to subsequent dieback. We compared different vegetation indices and applied time series analysis to detect declining trends and assessed accuracy according to tree species and canopy size. Additionally, aerial images provided by Google and Bing were used for validation. Overall, NDVI and EVI enabled to identify most of the affected individuals being limited by small canopy sizes. Among the different methods, monotonic and median trends yielded accurate estimates of total affected area. The method developed is intended to be applied with Sentinel-2 images in order to evaluate the limitations of spatial resolution, after decommissioning of Venus VM5 satellite.
