AU  - Fekety, PA
AU  - Vogeler, JC
AU  - Filippelli, SK
AU  - Nelson, MD
TI  - Forest disturbance attribution and sensitivity to harvest detection with Landsat in the Great Lakes region, USA
T2  - FOREST ECOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT
AB  - The wide variety of forest types and management goals in the Great Lakes region of the USA makes consistent spatial products depicting forest disturbance crucial to natural resource monitoring and planning. Timber harvesting is a common and important ecological disturbance in the region, yet the sensitivity of disturbance mapping to different harvest types is unknown, which could mean certain disturbances are poorly captured in current maps. In this study, we used Landsat time series of the Great Lakes region to create a 3-class model that identified and annually mapped undisturbed forest, disturbed forest, and non-forest. Additionally, we interpreted a sample of forest disturbances to create a classification model that further attributed the disturbed forest into 5 classes (Conversion, Fire, Flood, Harvest, Other). Using known harvest activities on US Forest Service lands, we determined agreement between our annual disturbance maps and various harvest types. Finally, we used an annual canopy cover product to investigate the agreement between harvest identification success and the amount of canopy removed during harvest. While the annual 3-class maps had a mean overall accuracy of 88.7 %, the disturbance attribution classification had producer's accuracies ranging between 1.5 % for Floods and 87.9 % for Fires and user's accuracies ranging between 32.4 % for the Other class and 84.1 % for Fires. Identification of harvests on US Forest Service lands depended strongly on harvest intensity. Intense harvests, such as coppice and stand clearcuts, were correctly identified 93 % and 74 % of the time, respectively, while less intense activities such as commercial thinning and single-tree selection were identified 26 % and 11 % of the time, respectively. Harvests that reduced canopy cover by less than 10 percentage points were successfully identified 13 % of the time, and harvests that removed greater than 30 percentage points of canopy cover were rarely missed (93 % identified). These maps provide spatially explicit and temporally extensive data on forest disturbance and harvest type to land managers and researchers within the Great Lakes region, as well as providing a basis for future research further characterizing harvest activities with Landsat time series methodologies.
