TI  - Employing calibrated long time-series of EOS data for retrospective studies of grazing induced land degradation: The DeMon-II project
T2  - DECADE OF TRANS-EUROPEAN REMOTE SENSING COOPERATION
CP  - 20th Annual Symposium of the European-Association-of-Remote-Sensing-Laboratories (EARSeL)
AB  - The Mediterranean Basin has been under enormous ecological pressure since historical times, from extensive deforestation and land use changes in ancient history to recent manifestations in agriculture, industry and tourism. In the frame of the DeMon-II project carried out under the Fourth Framework Programme of the European Commission, one of the pilot studies focussed on mountainous ecosystems on the island of Crete, Greece. In order to identify areas being threatened by or subject to degradation, an extended time series of Landsat TM and MSS data covering central Crete from 1977 until 1997 was analysed. By linking ground truth data to the results from satellite image interpretation it was possible to establish a retrospective analysis of degradation processes. A combination of trend analysis and knowledge-based threshold parameters yielded information on the spatial distribution of environmental changes over 20 years.
